Maha Mrityunjay Temple is a Hindu Temple dedicated to Hindu God Shiva, situated in Nagaon, Assam, India.This Temple is special in its architectural sense as it is built in a form a Shivling. It is the Worlds largest Shivalinga, at the height of 126 foot.This feature is made it unique and very attractive for the devotees.

_Construction of temple was initiated in 2003 by Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharaj, this place is where he used to meditate and is the location where Guru Shukracharya performed Mahamrityunjaya Mantra. Basis of this thought Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharajas had chosen this place for temple construction (Pran Pratishta). The initial planning for the construction started in the year 2003 but after several attempts by other architects and engineers,the final engineering and design work was carried by Er. Narayan Sharma. The temple is also very significant due to reflection of mastery in engineering.

name: Harsha Batra
review_text:
Maha Mrityunjay Temple: A Spiritual Oasis

The Maha Mrityunjay Temple, nestled in the serene village of Barangatoli, Nagaon, stands as a testament to devotion and architectural marvel. Devotees and visitors alike find solace within its sacred precincts. Lets explore the temples highlights:

1. The Majestic Shivlinga:
The temples centerpiece is a colossal 126-foot-tall shivlinga made of black stone. This sacred symbol of Lord Shiva radiates a powerful energy, drawing devotees from far and wide. The circular base houses the sanctum sanctorum, where the shivlinga resides. Its sheer size evokes awe and reverence.

2. Architectural Splendor:
As you approach the temple, the intricate carvings on the outer walls catch your eye. Skilled artisans have adorned the structure with delicate motifs, depicting mythological scenes and celestial beings. The towering shivlinga itself is a marvel of engineering. Its symmetry and proportions reflect the devotion and craftsmanship of those who built it.

3. Spiritual Atmosphere:
Unlike bustling temples, the Maha Mrityunjay Temple offers a tranquil environment. The absence of pushy vendors and noisy crowds allows visitors to connect with their inner selves. The priests, clad in saffron robes, perform rituals with quiet devotion. Their rhythmic chants resonate through the temple, creating an aura of spirituality.

4. Prayer and Reflection:
Devotees come here seeking blessings, healing, and protection. Many recite the Maha Mrityunjaya Mantra, believed to grant victory over death and bestow longevity. The temples serene ambiance encourages introspection. Visitors sit cross-legged, eyes closed, lost in prayer or meditation.

5. Festivals and Celebrations:
During Maha Shivaratri, the temple comes alive with festivities. Devotees fast, chant hymns, and offer bilva leaves and water to Lord Shiva. The annual Shravan Maas sees a steady stream of pilgrims, carrying water from the nearby Brahmaputra River to pour over the shivlinga.

Whether you seek spiritual enlightenment, architectural beauty, or simply a moment of peace, the Maha Mrityunjay Temple invites you to experience its divine energy.

This temple is located at Puranigudam in Nagaon district of Assam. This temple is constructed in the shape of a large Shivling with a height of 126 feet and is the World's tallest Shivalinga. It is believed that the great sage shukracharya performed Mahamrityunjaya yagya here.
The temple is beautiful and has two storeys. While the devotees can offer their prayers and worship on the first floor the ground floor is for prasad distribution. The temple remains closed from 12:30 PM to 1:30 PM and during this time the devotees are served khichdi on the ground floor for free.
There is a separate lamp house for lighting diyas and agarbattis.
Separate washrooms for Gents and Ladies are available and also provision for drinking water is available.
There is plenty of space for two-wheeler and four-wheeler parking. In all a very good place to visit with family.

A Visit Steeped in Serenity: My Uplifting Experience at the Maha Mrityunjay Temple
Theres a certain magic that permeates sacred spaces. And let me tell you, the Maha Mrityunjay Temple is brimming with it! From the moment I stepped onto the grounds, a wave of peace washed over me.

Perhaps it was the sheer scale of the place. Towering above me was the worlds largest Shivalinga, a majestic structure that whispered of devotion and history. Or maybe it was the energy of fellow devotees, their chants and prayers filling the air with a sense of shared purpose.

Whatever the reason, I found myself enveloped in a feeling of immense positivity. The worries that usually clung to me seemed to melt away, replaced by a sense of calm and tranquility.

name: Prashant Dumbre
review_text:
My visit to the Maha Mrityunjay Temple left me with mixed feelings, and unfortunately, I cant rate it higher than two stars.

While the temple holds cultural significance and has a serene atmosphere, my overall experience was marred by a few notable drawbacks. Firstly, the maintenance of the premises could be improved. There were visible signs of wear and tear, and certain areas seemed neglected.

The lack of clear information for visitors was a significant downside. There were minimal signages or guides to explain the historical or cultural aspects of the temple. As a result, the visit felt somewhat disconnected, and I couldnt fully appreciate the significance of the temple and its rituals.

Another point of concern was the cleanliness of the surroundings. The temple premises could benefit from better upkeep, as there were instances of litter and debris, detracting from the spiritual ambiance.

Additionally, I found the accessibility to be somewhat challenging, especially for elderly visitors or those with mobility issues. The infrastructure and facilities could be enhanced to accommodate a broader range of visitors.

The temple staff were not polite, there was a lack of proactive assistance or engagement.

In summary, the Maha Mrityunjay Temple has potential, but there are crucial areas that need attention. With improvements in maintenance, information dissemination, cleanliness, and accessibility, this temple could offer a more fulfilling experience for devotees and tourists alike.

name: Suman Sinha
review_text:
As the sun rises over the holy city of Ujjain, the Maha Mrityunjay Temple emerges as a spiritual beacon, encapsulating the essence of devotion and divine energy. Dedicated to Lord Shiva, the temple holds a unique significance as a place where the Maha Mrityunjay Mantra is chanted fervently, believed to bestow protection from mortal fears and grant inner strength.

Nestled on the banks of the Shipra River, the temples architecture seamlessly blends traditional design elements with intricate carvings, creating a sacred ambiance. Pilgrims, clad in saffron robes, ascend the steps to enter the sanctum sanctorum, where the presiding deity, a lingam representing Lord Shiva, is worshipped with profound reverence.

The Maha Mrityunjay Mantra, Om Tryambakam Yajamahe, Sugandhim Pushtivardhanam, Urvarukamiva Bandhanan, Mrityor Mukshiya Maamritat, resonates through the temple, creating an atmosphere charged with spiritual vibrations. Devotees believe in the mantras potency to conquer the fear of death and attain spiritual liberation.

The temples surroundings exude tranquility, offering a serene space for meditation and introspection. Festivals, especially Maha Shivaratri, witness an influx of devotees who seek blessings and engage in religious rituals, enhancing the temples vibrancy.

Beyond its religious significance, the Maha Mrityunjay Temple serves as a cultural and architectural gem, reflecting the rich heritage of Ujjain. The temples allure lies not only in its physical splendor but in the profound spiritual experiences it offers to those who embark on a pilgrimage to this sacred abode, seeking solace and divine grace in the heart of Ujjain.

name: Pallab Jyoti Nath
review_text:
Certainly! Heres a description of maha mrityunjay temple:

Nestled within a serene landscape, the temple stands as a testament to devotion and tranquility. Its majestic entrance, adorned with intricate carvings and vibrant colors, welcomes visitors into a realm of spirituality. As you step inside, the soothing aroma of incense fills the air, creating an atmosphere of reverence.

The main hall boasts towering pillars intricately etched with scenes from ancient scriptures and legends, while sunlight filters through stained glass windows, casting a warm and ethereal glow. Devotees, both young and old, can be seen offering prayers, lighting candles, and bowing in front of ornate altars adorned with idols of various deities.

Outside the main hall, a courtyard adorned with meticulously landscaped gardens offers a peaceful space for meditation and reflection. The rhythmic chants of priests performing rituals reverberate, creating a harmonious symphony that resonates with the soul. Visitors can also find small stalls selling flowers, incense, and religious artifacts, adding to the temples vibrant atmosphere.

Whether one seeks solace, enlightenment, or a connection with the divine, this temple stands as a sacred sanctuary where the spiritual and the earthly merge in a harmonious dance.

name: Bhaba Jyoti Nath
review_text:
Maha Mrityunjay Temple is a prominent Hindu temple in Nagaon District, Assam, India. The temple is dedicated to Lord Shiva, who is worshiped as Maha Mrityunjay, the god of healing and rejuvenation.

The temple is a sacred pilgrimage site for Hindus and is believed to have immense spiritual significance. Devotees from all over the world visit this temple to offer prayers and seek blessings from Lord Shiva.

According to the locals, the temple has a rich historical and cultural significance and is believed to date back to the rule of the Ahom Dynasty. The temple architecture is unique and showcases a blend of local Assamese and Hindu tradition. The temple premises are well-maintained, and the peaceful atmosphere of the temple is very soothing.

Overall, Maha Mrityunjay Temple Nagaon is a beautiful temple, and it is worth visiting if you are in the Nagaon district and want to explore the deep-rooted spiritual beliefs of the Assamese people.

name: Ankit Singh
review_text: Maha Mrityunjay Temple is a Hindu Temple dedicated to Hindu God Shiva, situated in Nagaon, Assam, India. This Temple is special in its architectural sense as it is built in a form a Shivling. It is the Worlds largest Shivaling, at the height of 126 foot. This feature is made it unique and very attractive for the devotees. The Temple Inauguration was done by Pran Pratishta Mahotsav, worship (Puja) was stated on 22 Feb and ended on 25 Feb 2021, As special guest the Union Home Minister Mr. Amit Shah, Minister of Health and Education in Assam Dr. Himanta Biswa Sarma and Ex. Chief Minister of Assam Mr. Sarbananda Sonowal had participated the puja and Yagna of Maha Mrityunjay Temple. 108 Yagna Kundas was established for the Yagna and around 250 priests came from Tamil Nadu to perform the Pran Pratishta Yagna. After completion of Pran Pratishta Yagna the Temple was opened for devotees from 26 Feb 2021.

name: Madhulika Liddle
review_text:
This huge Shiv Temple is located just about 5 minutes' drive off the main Guwahati-Kaziranga highway. It's a much revered spot for Shiv devotees, and is actually worth visiting even for people just interested in impressive architecture. The temple is shaped in the form of a massive, 126' tall shivlinga, made of black stone, sitting atop a circular stone platform. The temple's sanctum sanctorum is situated in the circular base of the shivlinga.

Unlike most other popular temples, this one has no people clamouring to sell you pooja items or take you on an express darshan. The priests too are quiet and not pushy.

name: prasenjit panda
review_text: Excellent architecture. Something different. Lingam shaped temple. I saw such temple for the first time. Huge. Wonderful surrounding. If you take pic from a particular angle it looks like a DIA. Multiple gates to enter. Not that crowded on a Monday afternoon. Opens after a break of an HR or so for Bhoga at 1330. I reached 1345. Had comfortable darshan. People were there but not in insane number. Very organized and orderly. All age groups. Separate place for dia. Clean campus. Surrounding clean. View good from all angles. Enough parking place. We didnt need to give any parking fee to anyone. No pujari forces you to do any specific Puja. No one demands money unlike many other places. Road leading to the temple well maintained and not very far from the National Highway 735/37. Road is slimmer than NH obviously but free of potholes. Few elephant on the way. Kids took pic with them. Wont take more than 30-45 min from total trip to get back to national highway after leaving the same for temple darshan. A very good experience. Roughly about 20 km away from Nawagaon in Assam ( not exactly but somewhere in the same range). Recommended for those believe in Shiv bhagwan and visiting Assam for Kaziranga/ travelling through Nawagaon by NH 735/37. A peaceful surrounding.

name: bitupon saikia Amazon
review_text:
The Maha Mrityunjay Temple is a Hindu temple dedicated to Lord Shiva located in Purigudam, Nagaon district of Assam.[1] Construction of the temple was completed in February The temple is architecturally modeled on a huge Shiva Linga.[2][3] The temple is the largest Shiva Linga in the world at 126 feet tall.
The construction of the temple was started in 2003 by Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharaj. He used this place for meditation and believes that the giant guru Shukracharya performed the religious rituals of the Maha Mrityunjaya Mantra here in ancient times according to mythological beliefs. Based on this thought, Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharaj chose this place for the construction of the temple. Initial planning for the construction began in 2003 but after several attempts by other architects and engineers, the final engineering and design work was borne by A. Narayan Sharma. The temple is very important for its reflection of mastery in engineering.[5][6]

name: Vishal Poudyal (NikhilRaj)
review_text:
I have been to this place twice, and the only thing I could feel is that it is developing day by day. Some of the things I felt like highlighting is
* This place seriously need to have grass and carpets.In case of sunny day, the whole of floor gets heated like fire and it is difficult for most of the people to even walk bare foot. I have witnessed some old people struggling to walk and stand. My heart melted for those couple. I wished they had some sort of wings or anything that could make them fly.
* This place has free parking, which I liked very much. But these people who sells agarbatti, diya and prasadam forces you to buy from their shop, but dont fall to that trap, you can take your car/vehicle inside the campus itself and that is also free!
* If you go there in the evening, the lights are things which you will love it there!
* If you want to do the darshana, reach their before 12 noon or after 1:30PM. (It might change though)
* If you want to arpan milk and water you can bring it in some metal container. It will be directly poured over the lingam. However, prasadam will also be given, but not on lingam, directly!
Thats all for now, if something comes up, I will add to it!

History
Edit
Construction of temple was initiated in 2003 by Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharaj, this place is where he used to meditate and is the location where Guru Shukracharya performed Mahamrityunjaya Mantra. Basis of this thought Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharajas had chosen this place for temple construction (Pran Pratishta). The initial planning for the construction started in the year 2003 but after several attempts by other architects and engineers,the final engineering and design work was carried by Er. Narayan Sharma. The temple is also very significant due to reflection of mastery in engineering.

Inauguration and Pran Pratishta Mahotsav
Edit
The Temple Inauguration was done by Pran Pratishta Mahotsav, worship (Puja) was stated on 22 Feb and ended on 25 Feb 2021,As special guest the Union Home Minister Mr. Amit Shah, Minister of Health and Education in Assam Dr. Himanta Biswa Sarma and Ex. Chief Minister of Assam Mr. Sarbananda Sonowal had participated the puja and Yagna of Maha Mrityunjay Temple.108 Yagna Kundas was established for the Yagna and around 250 priests came from Tamil Nadu to perform the Pran Pratishta Yagna.[10] After completion of Pran Pratishta Yagna the Temple was opened for devotees from 26 Feb 2021.

name: Supritom Borkataky
review_text: While you visit any temple or a devotional institute for some inner peace or spiritual calmness, it usually creates a positive vibes right through your spine, brain, heart and connects you stronger than you know, that theories beyond any external emphasizing element...but in this particular temple, neither I felt any devotion, nor any quiver.. sensed just another business establishment, nothing special... Observed a complete hotch-potch management from every aspect, except a few smooth road connectivity towards it... Overpriced parking & Prasad stalls, confused security, filthy premises, uncontrollable crowds etc .. you have to submit your offerings in a separate space and you wont get anything back...for Prasad, you need to visit a separate stall at a distance with no hygienic protocol..even to take a tilak or worshipped flower, you need to pay extra to other purohits who sit around outside the puja premise...priests are also appeared non Assamese folks, who have no idea about Assam or its culture..no clean washroom to handle such a huge crowd, no proper drinking water facility, no prayer room for devotees, no proper shoe keeping racks, no shelter/rest room for common/old people, rather you can see 2 big helipads in outer circle..looking at the place, seems like heavy amount of environmental ecology are compromised while building this project...still construction is going on, but no tree has planted yet to manage some ecological balance.. I wouldnt have given the 3 star if its not somehow involved with Baba Bholenath  for such disaster institution.. I hope it would do some betterment for a positive impact in near future so everyone gets benefitted from all around...

name: Anupal Bharali
review_text:
Visited yesterdsy (on 8-Feb-2022). A holy place with a huge Shiva linga that automatically instills devotion in your heart.

There is a specified place outside the temple to put the lighted earthen lamps (diyas). A good arrangement.

We offered fruits, dry fruits etc as Prasad. The priest kept a part for the mandir and returned the rest after performing prayers with our Prasad.

We had gone there with our brand new car. One of the priests came to our car and performed prayers, drew swastika, put garlands on the car. It was so satisfying.

The main temple is complete. Now they are developing the surroundings with gardens and water fountains etc. It will be even more beautiful once these are completed.

There is also a residential school for Vedic Studies. It can be seen in one of the photos at the background with the temple entrance in the foreground.

Overall a very satisfying experience.

name: Rinto Chaudhury
review_text: Construction of temple was initiated in 2003 by Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharajas, this place he was used to meditate and according to him demon guru Shukracharya performed Maha Mrityunjay (Mantra) religious rituals here in ancient times as per mythological beliefs. Basis of this thought Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharajas had chosen this place for temple construction (Pran Pratishta). The initial planning for the construction started in the year 2003 but after several attempts by other architects and engineers,the final engineering and design work was carried by Er. Narayan Sharma. The temple is also very significant due to reflection of mastery in engineering. The Temple Inauguration was done by Pran Pratishta Mahotsav, worship (Puja) was stated on 22 Feb and ended on 25 Feb 2021, As special guest the Union Home Minister Mr. Amit Shah and Ex. Chief Minister of Assam Mr.Sarbananda Sonowal had participated the puja and Yagna of Maha Mrityunjay Temple. 108 Yagna Kundas was established for the Yagna and around 250 priests came from Tamil Nadu to perform the Pran Pratishta Yagna. After completion of Pran Pratishta Yagna then Temple was opened for normal devotees from 26 Feb 2021. Massive earthquake reported on 28 April 2021 in Assam and NE Region measured 6.7 in the richter scale and due that that jolt the minor crack observed in upper part of 126 feet of temple which can be termed as ornamental damage and no structural damage has occurred.

name: Ujjal Bora
review_text:
Maha Mrityunjay Temple is a Hindu Temple shrine dedicated to Hindu God Shiva situated on Nagaon Assam India. This Temple is newly constructed and completed on Feb 2021. Temple has worlds largest 126-foot-tall Shivalinga,this feature is made it unique and very attractive for the devotees.
Construction of temple was initiated in 2003 by Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharajas, this place he was used to meditate and according to him demon guru Shukracharya performed Maha Mrityunjay (Mantra) religious rituals here in ancient times as per mythological beliefs. Basis of this thought Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharajas had chosen this place for temple construction (Pran Pratishta). The initial planning for the construction started in the year 2003 but after several attempts by other architects and engineers,the final engineering and design work was carried by Er. Narayan Sharma. The temple is also very significant due to reflection of mastery in engineering.

name: Ripunjay Nath
review_text:
It is the biggest Shiv Ling in the world. The environment of the temple is very peaceful. On Sundays and Mondays it gets a bit crowded. The temple is surrounded by a number of shops where you get earthen lamps and other puja related stuff. One good thing of this place that I personally found is that you cannot burn the earthen lamps and inscence sticks inside the temple. Instead there is a small house built near the main structure of the temple which is ment to burn earthen lamps and inscence sticks. The pandits of the temple are well learned people. You can perform personal pujas in the temple if you contact the authorities one or two days before performing the puja.
The temple has got a large area for parking your bikes, cars and scooters. There are also nearby areas for paid parking owned by the people nearby. There is a government guest house just beside the temple which is really beautiful and very clean. Besides parking space for cars and bikes there are also two helipads nearby the temple. This is in case you prefer to go on a private helicopter from Guwahati airport. Lastly I would like to say that you will really love it once you visit this temple.

name: Rishikesh Sutradhar
review_text:
The Maha Mrityunjay Temple in Puranigudan, Nagaon is now quite renowned for the record of constructing the 126 feet tall Shiva linga which is the largest Shiva Linga in the world.

The construction commenced in the year 2003 which was initiated by Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharajas this was his place where he used to meditate.

As per the mythological beliefs of the Maharaj, during the historic period, Shukracharya, the guru of the Daityas or Asuras performed religious rituals where the temple is situated.

It is still in the development stage and apart from the Shiva-Linga there is nothing else nearby, it situated in a remote place and the area is backward. Very few shops are present nearby, it has car parking facility. Cool and Calm place for Shiv-Bhakts to witness the giant construction and get mesmerized.

name: ARYAN GUPTA (VAIBHAV)
review_text:
Maha Mrityunjaya Temple is the largest Shiva Linga temple in Asia. It is located in Kalajugi near Kalagaon city. This Shi Linga is 126 feet in height.

The Pooja Pran Pratishtha Mahotsav of Maha Mrityunjay Temple was held from 22nd February to 25th February. The temple has opened for all devotees from 26th February.

The construction of the temple started in 2003 under the guidance of Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharaj. Bhrigu Giri Maharaj chose this place after doing spiritual practice. According to Daityaraja, in ancient times, demon guru Shukracharya used to perform yagya at the site of the temple.

About 250 priests from Tamil Nadu have come to perform Pran Pratistha Yagya in the temple.

108 Yagya Kunds have been built and all arrangements have been made so that all the priests can perform the grand Yagya.

name: Swamy Basana
review_text:
NAGAON: The festival of Pran Pratishta of Mritunjay temple in Puranigudan, Nagaon will be ending today which commenced on 22nd February.

The Maha Mrityunjay Temple in Puranigudan, Nagaon is now quite renowned for the record of constructing the 126 feet tall Shiva linga which is the largest Shiva Linga in the world.

The construction commenced in the year 2003 which was initiated by Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharajas this was his place where he used to meditate.

As per the mythological beliefs of the Maharaj, during the historic period, Shukracharya, the guru of the Daityas or Asuras performed religious rituals where the temple is situated.

The devotees are allowed to worship in the temple from the 26th of February.

According to a salient priest around two fifty priests, all the way from Tamil Nadu have participated to perform all the rituals of the ceremony.

The General Secretary of the temple committee, Jitu Goswami said that it is a great thing that eventually the dreams of the founder of the temple, Acharya Bhrigu Giri Maharaj has been fulfilled as it was his long and earnest wish for this temple. He also thanked everyone for the contribution to build this phenomenal temple and wished everyones presence in the temples inaugural event.

According to ancient belief, this is where Maharishi Shukracharya created the Mahamrityunjaya Mantra and Mrit Sanjivani after doing years of sadhana and meditation. Mahamrityunjaya Mantra is chanted for good mental and physical health and well-being and to gain immortality as far as my understanding goes.
And the Mrit Sanjivani was used to bring the dead back into life. This knowledge was only transferred by the guru to the select few students in the guru shishya parampara of learning according to what I know from old stories and heresay.
This place after being dug and rediscovered the temple committee is constructing a huge Shiv Linga structure which would get completed in a few years time. Right now there is a small temple of Lord Shiva once you enter the gate. Behind it is the huge structure of Shiv Linga which is being built. Right underneath is the main holy shrine ( the place of meditation of Maharishi Shukracharya) where the temple committee has placed a Shiv Linga and a board stating the history of the place.
